Gutach: Even more safety for pedestrians
They are less than 100 metres apart: on Tuesday, the new B 33 pedestrian traffic light at the village car park was put into operation in Gutach - within sight of the older town hall traffic light.
Two turbines so close to each other: intention or prank?
The Mayor of London gave a clear answer to that question yesterday.
"The town hall traffic light was installed at that time because it secures the way to school," Eckert explained yesterday.
The Kluser traffic lights secure both cyclists and bus passengers and the residents of the mountain.
The plant, which was officially put into operation yesterday, is important for the intersection of Sulzbachweg and Kirchstraße.
We have the museum, two churches, the spa park, the bus stop, a doctor and a bank as well as the traffic flow from the residential area › Grub ‹.
"Due to the high traffic and pedestrian traffic, another traffic light had to be set up for their safety," Eckert said.
This is also confirmed by Peter Arnold from the Offenburg district office.
"According to current measurements, about 12,000 vehicles pass through the municipality of Gutach on the B 33 every day, of which about ten percent are heavy goods vehicles," Arnold emphasises.
Therefore the construction of a further traffic light is more than necessary: "Safety simply proceeds here," so Arnold.
Altogether four traffic shows were accomplished, also a roundabout was considered, however because of the narrowness in the crossing area Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße again discarded.
According to Arnold, everything was tested beforehand when the traffic light poles were chosen: "By means of a van specially loaded with particularly long logs for us, we tested whether these vehicles could exit Sulzbachweg onto the B 33 without bending over the traffic light poles."
The traffic light system itself, which costs around 15,000 euros, is "the most modern on the market at the moment," explained Arnold.
The system is equipped with coloured LEDs that glow so powerfully that the lights are clearly visible to drivers, even in low-lying sunlight, for example.
And it is also economical: The older lighting systems consume around 100 watts, the new ones just eight watts.
There are three lighting systems per direction of travel.
Arnold explained the technology of the new facility: It is equipped with two radar sensors.
When the pedestrian presses the traffic light button, the upper radar sensor tests the traffic situation.
If the road is clear, the pedestrian will immediately get green; if not, it will take about 15 seconds.
A further radar sensor checks whether the green phase for the pedestrian can be completed.
"If a group of people or people with mobility difficulties cross the road, the green period will be extended, so everyone can safely cross the road," Mr Arnold said.
Of course, the driver has to think as a partner and observe the road surface.
