A black box in the car?
US road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the crumbling highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every kilometre driven and report the information to authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to overhaul the outdated system for funding US roads.
The normally boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colourful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups, arguing that the government should be able to use the small boxes to record miles driven - and possibly where they were driven - and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The Tea Party is appalled.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on how to proceed, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how they can switch over the next decade to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This really is a must for our country.
"It's not something we're just going to use," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven by all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes is going to change.
The technology is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded by taxes paid by Americans at the pump, is broke.
But America doesn't fill up as much as it used to.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state petroleum tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 cents per liter) has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax by even a cent when the price of petrol is high.
"The gasoline tax is just not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most sensible long-term alternative," he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea has resonated with urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behavior to reduce congestion and climate-damaging emissions.
California planners rely on the system to devise strategies to meet the state's ambitious, statutory climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also taken with the idea of having drivers pay according to the distance travelled.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole," said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US Transportation secretaries, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The US Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the House majority blocked the move, responding to concerns from rural lawmakers representing people who often have to travel many miles to work or the city on a daily basis.
Several states and major cities are nonetheless moving in this direction on their own.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees to the state instead of the fuel tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently fitted with the devices, motorists were skeptical that the government could track their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, director of strategy and results management at Nevada's Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test began, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website, "It would be relatively easy to turn tachographs into full-blown surveillance devices."
There was no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on individuals "daily movements.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that will allow the state to track the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
That, Khan said, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not compete to help states tax motorists.
Rather, their aim was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for motor insurance, where drivers are expected to pay on the basis of miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also of interest to road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving motorists a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose not to use a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all state residents.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept to a wary public by equipping the devices with more features than fewer.
In New York City, transportation officials want to develop a taxation device that can also pay for parking, pay for insurance only for miles driven, and collect real-time speed data from other vehicles to help drivers avoid traffic jams.
"Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," a city planning document says.
Some traffic planners, however, wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge red herring.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off charge or annual levy could be imposed on motorists with hybrid or other vehicles that use little petrol, so that they too pay their fair share.
"There is no reason for surgery if one aspirin is sufficient," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislative and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will be worried about their privacy and many other things.
