US border: 'super-tunnels' for drug smuggling discovered
Investigators have discovered and shut down a "super-tunnel" for drug smuggling along the Mexico-US border.
According to US Customs, the more than 500 metre long pipe between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railway tracks and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested and eight tons of marijuana and nearly 150 kilograms of cocaine were seized.
According to the information, the tunnel had not yet been used.
"These cartels are stupid if they think they can dig under the radar," U.S. District Attorney for the Southern District of California Laura Duffy said at a news conference outside a San Diego warehouse where one end of the tunnel was discovered.
Turning to the drug gangs, Duffy said: "If you keep building these tunnels and trying to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both U.S. authorities and Mexican security forces are engaged in an ongoing battle against drug cartels.
More than 77,000 people have been killed in Mexico related to drug-related crime since 2006.
Constructed by experts
Due to the complex equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took around a year.
The track layout was equipped in such a way that electrically driven cars could be used there.
On the Mexican side, the entrance is located in a building 80 meters from the border.
According to authorities, a ladder leads 20 meters down to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross-section of 1.20 metres in height and 90 centimetres in width.
It would also have been suitable for encouraging illegal immigration to the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine discovery.
The third, a Mexican, was arrested for the marijuana seized.
All three face the maximum penalty of life imprisonment, officials said.
Eight such tunnels have been discovered since 2006, the San Diego news conference said.
But it is the first time cocaine has been found in such a tunnel.
Cocaine is usually smuggled in smaller quantities and not through tunnels.
This shows the "desperation" of the drug gangs, whose traditional routes have now been cut off, said Bill Sherman of the DEA Drug Enforcement Administration in San Diego.
They would do anything to get into the US.
No details were released about those arrested, at least one of whom was Mexican, it said.
They face up to ten years in prison.
