Council sets sights on rail tracks
Is the level crossing "Am Hirschen" to be extensively modified in order to increase traffic safety?
Yes, the local councils have decided.
Schiltach will have to pay EUR 220 000 for this.
Deutsche Bahn wants to improve the Kinzigtal railway line next year.
In particular, safety at level crossings is to be increased - trains collide with other vehicles on a regular basis throughout Germany.
If the municipalities agree to the renovation measures, they must contribute one third of the costs, the remainder is shared between the railway and the federal government.
Schiltach's master builder Roland Grießhaber explained the special features of the "Am Hirschen" rail crossing to the local council.
There, the city plans to build a bulge at the level of the mouth of the tunnel to the west of the railway tracks.
Larger vehicles, such as those transporting long timber, could also stand in oncoming traffic without having to block the tracks.
Grießhaber therefore proposed to construct a necessary retaining wall so that the city could widen the adjacent road in due course to ensure a smooth flow of traffic.
This was controversially discussed in the local council, as some councils questioned the necessity of widening the roads: Thomas Kipp summed up the mood of the critics with his statement: "Do we have to take so much money in our hands because of so few vehicles?"
Mayor Thomas Haas disagreed: The "Hirschen" level crossing is regularly used for transporting long timber.
Even timber from the "Kuhbach" area is sometimes transported along this route, because the vehicles, which are up to 20 metres long, cannot use the route at the Häberlesbrücke bridge because they cannot turn into the main road there.
In addition, the route serves as a diversion for those vehicles that are not allowed to use the tunnel when the main road is closed, Haas argued.
Since it is foreseeable that Kirchberg and Schlossberg tunnels will have to be rebuilt and refurbished, as is currently the case in Wolfach, the level crossing "Am" Hirschen "could also have an important traffic significance for a longer period of time.
Councils agreed to investigate the cost of the proposed widening of the road.
In spite of this, the reconstruction of the level crossing was approved by a majority with the proviso that the necessary retaining wall would be built in such a way that the city could expand the adjacent road in the direction of "Bahnhofstraße" to around 5.5 metres for traffic.
The conversion of the level crossing at the Trautwein tannery, on the other hand, could lead to a completely different problem concerning the access to the steeply rising "Geroltzhäuser Weg."
The administration had the railway's conversion plans examined by Ingenieurbüro Breinlinger, as it had doubts as to whether the planned connection of the Geroltzhäuser Weg would still be possible without further ado.
The investigation came to the conclusion that it could not be excluded that the inclination of the road could lead to longer vehicles sitting up.
Responsibility for this, in turn, lies with the city as a road haulier.
The modification could therefore lead to liability disputes.
Since both the timber removal and the turning function in the current state of construction, the conversion of the level crossing should not be approved, Haas argued.
At this point, the risk of a collision of the train with a vehicle standing on the crossing is also considerably lower than at the other level crossings, because there is a stop in the middle right next to it, to which there is a good visual connection.
Even trains from the main station would have to be braked at this point so that no collision was imminent.
The majority refused to approve the reconstruction of this level crossing, as the city of Schiltach "would have to bear the cost" of the problem with vehicles sitting on it, according to the councillors, as the railway could withdraw from responsibility after the completion of the construction work.
The committee considers the modifications at the level crossings "Vor Heubach" and "Vor Kuhbach," for which crossing agreements have already been made with the railway, to be unproblematic.
Esa Decides on Major Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Far planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the next few years.
Thirty proposals were up for grabs, with five still in the running.
Distant worlds.
Astronomers have already found more than 1,000 planets near other stars.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, nobody knows.
The choice is difficult: Should one search for gravitational waves?
Or rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and thereby perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that are being asked by the heads of the European Space Agency Esa.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to make a decisive contribution to research.
The budget for such "L-missions" is around one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space exploration met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were up for debate, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Numerous committees are examining the proposals and are consulting with researchers.
A final decision by the Scientific Programme Committee is expected in the next few days.
Esa has selected a total of four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, which was launched in 2007, should find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large clouds of gas - and thus the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
In order to investigate this question, the "Cheops" space telescope is to be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be examined in more detail.
The possibilities are limited, however, and Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to shed light on what conditions exist for the emergence of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system play an important role.
These processes can be investigated exemplarily in our solar system.
With the "Solar Orbiter," Esa has already approved an M-Class mission (where the budget is around half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is due to launch in 2017 and will observe the surface and activity of the sun closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, Esa is planning the first of a total of three L missions in the "Cosmic Vision" programme.
The "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it will reach Jupiter and study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show physicists the way to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, which consists of stars, planets and living beings like ourselves, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy, which accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid," Esa has already approved an M mission, the launch of which is scheduled for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe is to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time across the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the competition.
According to many experts, "E-Lisa," a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves, has the best chance of being approved as an L-mission.
Physicists understand this to mean changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could do it, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission envisages a detector consisting of two or three probes to be stationed in space.
In contrast to systems on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that originated in the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena," which will explore black holes, "Icy Planets," another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism," a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder," which will detect and study Earth-like planets.
Among other things, proposals for sample return transport from Mars, for research into the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as solar physics, have already been rejected.
