Frontier Airlines Charges for Hand Baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 to passengers who want to stow carry-on luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for a piece of carry-on baggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although Wednesday's announcement said passengers would be allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to carry-on baggage in the overhead compartment and small bags under the seat will continue to be free of charge.
Frontier said it charged $25 if the fee was paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who paid at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee was aimed at getting travelers to pay upfront.
"We don't want to calculate that sum," she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second pieces of checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who have tried to avoid them have therefore stuffed as much as possible into their hand luggage, with the result that the overhead compartments above the seat are often overcrowded.
Charges are one way to encourage passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
It was all about Frontier's most loyal customers, who had made it clear that it was becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline's website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at the Frontier gate may be allowed to take one piece of baggage free of charge, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of baggage.
O'Malley said Frontier's website and check-in procedures will be changed so that passengers are informed of the fee before they get to the gate.
Frontier's new carry-on fee won't come into effect until the summer, but a precise date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that transporting luggage costs money and passengers should pay for the service if they want it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage fees as a sign that airlines are raising enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most have so far avoided charges for carry-on luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for carry-on baggage three years ago, and Allegiant Air, another low-cost carrier, followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungary's Wizz Air, said Jay Sorensen, an airline consultant who is closely monitoring the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that Spirit's carry-on fee brought in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a senior position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious to see what would await him at the gate if passengers were confronted with the company's unusual carry-on fee.
"The boarding process has been one of the smoothest I have experienced in my aviation career," he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and tangible discussions at the gate.
"The plane was full," he said, "and the boarding went smoothly."
Frontier also follows Spirit on the $2 charge for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company said passengers who bought lemonade or juice would be allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be refilled for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed it seven months later after passengers complained and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier's move to charge for carry-on luggage when passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to steer customers to its own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies such as Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides an incentive for all airlines to encourage passengers to buy directly from them, rather than through an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, the company began issuing half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agent.
On Wednesday, the miles were cut again to 25 percent of the flight distance.
A Frontier flight over 1000 miles booked with a third-party provider will therefore earn customers only 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats only when purchasing directly from the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue fell 9 percent and flight capacity shrank nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released Wednesday by the parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has been trying to get a grip on Frontier's finances as part of the sale of the company.
