Bombardier profits fall after drop in deliveries and orders
Canadian aircraft and rail maker Bombardier Inc reported a 15 percent drop in net profit on Thursday after coming under pressure from declining orders and aircraft deliveries in the third quarter and contract problems in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide any new information on whether the aircraft could go commercial next September under the ambitious schedule.
The test aircraft's maiden flight a month and a half ago has been followed by only three other launches, making it doubtful whether the test phase will proceed as planned.
The results fell short of forecasts and led to a stock market plunge of more than eight percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his rating on Thursday from "outperform" to "sector perform," noting that the stock has limited price potential over the next quarter or two.
"While weaker aircraft deliveries were widely expected, we are clearly disappointed by the margin development in the transportation sector," Doerksen said in a letter to customers.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the aircraft's testing program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more sceptical about the program.
Bombardier hopes the CSeries will catapult the company into the lower end of the market, which is currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled to the public in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delays.
But binding orders for the 177 CSeries have so far been modest, as potential buyers await the results of flight tests to see if the company's claims about the new jet's fuel efficiency and cost-saving potential are true.
There are currently a total of 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and companies.
Chief executive Pierre Beaudoin said he was confident Bombardier would meet its target of 300 binding orders by the start of commercial use of the jet.
The company's management also assured analysts and media on Thursday that the program was on schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Beaudoin said on a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates had been scheduled during the plane's service life.
Every manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to take a first flight and then add a review period, which we did.
This happens throughout the flight programme.
The second of five test aircraft is expected to take off in the next few weeks, with the rest shortly thereafter, the company said.
However, analysts remain sceptical about whether the first customer will be able to commission a CSeries aircraft twelve months after the maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was reviewing the commissioning planning (EIS) and would update it in the coming months.
"The slow progress of the flight test - even though it appears to be in line with Bombardier's internal planning - reinforces our view that commissioning will be delayed until the first quarter of 2015," Doerksen said.
For the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share were unchanged at 9 cents.
Revenue fell slightly, to $4.1 billion from $4.2 billion.
Analysts had expected a profit of 10 cents per share and revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I / B / E / S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft maker says it delivered 45 aircraft this quarter, down from 57 last year.
Net orders fell from 83 aircraft to 26.
The aerospace division's backlog at September 30 was $32.9 billion, unchanged from December 31.
"In the aerospace sector, results were in line with our guidance, but low order intake and overall market conditions were disappointing," Beaudoin said.
Revenue in the aerospace division fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world's largest rail manufacturer, announced that revenue in this division rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The Transportation Division's backlog at September 30 was $32.6 billion, up slightly from December 31.
Profit margins in the transport sector have been affected by handling problems in some major contracts.
According to management, there will be new targets for the fourth quarter.
In afternoon trading on Thursday, Bombardier shares were down 8.5 percent at 4.83 Canadian dollars after it was also announced that Google's chief financial officer Patrick Pichette will join the board.
Brazil's Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft maker and Bombardier's closest rival, reported a 10 percent drop in quarterly profit on Thursday.
