Cocaine addict lawyer who warned drug boss of police investigation must go to jail
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed on information to underworld figure Neil Scarborough
Lawyer feared his secret drug addiction could come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison at Liverpool Crown Court
A prominent criminal defense lawyer who warned a drug lord against a major police investigation because he feared his secret drug addiction might be exposed has been sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld figure Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug-trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed "Bash" by detectives, was arrested at his home in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough, whom he represented in an earlier drug case.
Officers watched Scarborough, 32, deliver three bags of cocaine to the barrister's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was having dinner with colleagues at the Bar Association.
The investigation revealed that Ditta regularly used Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Over an eight-month period between January and August 2011, he attempted to obtain unauthorised information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were being monitored by police as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They were later arrested along with 32 others after police seized heroin and cocaine worth £1.5million and £200,000 in cash during a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction would become public.
Today, Ditta, who works for the law firm Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was found guilty and convicted of two counts of obstruction of justice at Liverpool Crown Court after a three-week trial.
He admitted cocaine possession during an earlier interview.
The lawyer was convicted after police investigating Scarborough found he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta's house and place the 60 percent purity drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer's dustbin.
Shortly after he delivered the drugs, Scarborough made regular phone calls to Ditta, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers "Ewood Park football ground.
The lawyer returned home, got the drugs and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
It was revealed in court that Ditta was a 'regular user' of cocaine after tests revealed Class A drugs in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied taking cocaine, saying he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, and claimed their discussion was covered by "legal secrecy."
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were seized and a sample of his hair was taken.
Under police questioning, he said he ran an office both at his home address and at work, and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
It was revealed in court that he had called key drug trafficking figures, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and told them what investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said: 'A criminal barrister should know better than anyone that you are not breaking the law.'
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defense attorney by engaging too much with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not just that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer supplying drugs to his lawyer.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, because he was the lawyer for those people.
But this went far beyond the boundaries of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He cooperated as far as possible with the police investigation so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr Ditta brought his profession into disrepute.
He was too close to certain clients, particularly Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing, claiming: 'If I was a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass information to Scarborough, I wouldn't wait 15 hours, I would do it straight away.'
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead, of Lancashire Police, said: 'Mr Ditta made the step from criminal defence lawyer to criminal the moment he started buying drugs from organised criminals.'
His cocaine addiction led to hopeless compromise and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organized crime, who instructed him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and inspire public confidence and confidence.
Ditta has betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind the façade of his profession.
Lancashire's Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Ditta, which also resulted in three convictions for possession of cocaine and obstruction of justice, underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We will find you and take you to court.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiracy to traffic heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other people involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences.
