What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
When designing the Internet service e-mail, was the secrecy of correspondence implemented in a similar way to conventional mail?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have failed to provide a stable basis for a sound exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When user "Anna" sends an e-mail to "Benni," are the computers of the two connected directly?
In the first step, Anna's e-mail program or browser sends the e-mail to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
Along the way, the mail can pass through several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read on their way through the net?
Most mails are read several times by software robots on the way.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam mail that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems such as GMail, the robot also detects the information Google needs to place context advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the e-mails?
The probability of unauthorised persons reading an e-mail is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or take note of e-mails.
Then there are the possible illegal spying operations.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from being read?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With great technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even readily possible to identify who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google on the e-mail market in Germany?
According to an August 2013 study by Convios Consulting, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the predominantly privately used mailboxes.
