And one that has grown to resemble a fossil: the first time I heard "independence means passport control" duck was at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point gets lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why would an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the tune of Europe?
Why swap the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project has officially died.
Across the EU, anti-EU parties are gaining ground, or seeking to jettison the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded only this year - won nearly five million votes in September's federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of Britain's Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, is turning out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the straitjacket into which each national economy is forced by adherence to the single currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits - that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pinned its members on exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters - and German politicians would like to keep that the way it is.
Without the possibility of a local currency depreciation, southern Europe finds itself at a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending, spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives imposed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen at Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is looming, especially in France, the EU's erstwhile cheerleader.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle for holding Germany in check and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, with which the struggling French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a crucial by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France, with 24% of the vote - a timely warning for Britain's Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right would automatically benefit the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newfound popularity among white working-class Frenchmen?
It wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU, anti-single currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections - and that is very possible - then, for the first time, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may stick to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of cozying up to the US.
But Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can choose to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put their money where their mouth is.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European grouping, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other, similar-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider following Norway's lead and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is, remarkably, the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 by rejecting the proposed (and implemented) cuts that Labour's Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have austerity policies imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
