Pawnshops are booming in Singapore as the crisis hits the middle class
At a pawn shop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bangle, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters "school fees.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, all my money is in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) a month as an administrative assistant and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
Indeed, such is demand in parts of Southeast Asia - where household debt is rising - that ValueMax, where it exchanged, became the third pawn shop to be listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Paying for jewelry is not only a quick way to get money - $1,300 Singapore dollars in Janani Amirthalinga's case - but almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual rate of 17%, just above the 15.4% charged by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that there is no need to check creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans can be made faster than with banks.
As a result, millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel the squeeze from rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit owing to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to make up the difference when the economy stutters.
This week, ratings agency Standard & Poor's cited growing household debt, mainly from rising mortgages, as a risk factor to Asian banks "credit worthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt to GDP ratios in Asia, according to the agency.
Malaysia tops the list with 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about high levels of consumer debt in Thailand, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
Data on Thursday showed continued export weakness and a slowdown in consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that as costs rise, people in the middle to lower end (of the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," said Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have amplified the trend toward pawning personal belongings, as people seize the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city-state's 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
Thailand's largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 per cent increase in customers in its branches in recent months.
Growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia - where the company has four stores - but also outside Asia, said Yeah Lee Ching, ValueMax's managing director.
The company is financing this with 60 per cent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it raised with the Singapore IPO this week.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offer cheaper rates than other lenders, but also don't directly increase debt.
"Customers lend out items they already own, and liquidating personal valuables doesn't add to household debt," she explains.
Pawnshops are increasingly accepted by society as short-term, hedged financing.
Not all pawnbrokers are in financial trouble, either.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax branches to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
"These include affluent people who borrow in the short term for a business or investment, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
