FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on planes (but can't make cell phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from take-off to landing, but not make phone calls, according to new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented would depend on the airline, FAA spokesman Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and equipment stowage rules in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on planes.
Delta and JetBlue were among those airlines.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to take it off again until the plane has reached an altitude of three kilometres and the captain gives the go-ahead.
When entering the landing area, passengers must turn it off again and must not take it off again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices during take-off, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft modified to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Flight Attendants Association, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regime is safely implemented - and we are working closely with the airline on this - both sides will benefit," said Glading.
Frankly, we are tired of feeling like watchdogs on this issue.
However, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometres remained banned, the authority said.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was forced to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, must continue to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during flight will also remain prohibited.
Phone calls are regulated by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert, told CBS News that cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Cellphones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially interfere with navigation devices, but because we at the FCC know that airborne transmission can also interfere with transmission towers," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue recommended last month that the government allow broader use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on use has increased in recent years.
Critics, such as Democratic Sen. Claire McCaskill of Missouri, say there are no valid safety grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget to turn off the device or ignore it.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of passenger-carried FM radios interfering with navigation and communications equipment, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they do not mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers when they reach altitude for several years.
Flyers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger planes should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when you turn the page.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Advocates for easing restrictions on passenger device use include Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to detect problems, but could not find any.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Association of Airline Passengers, said he believed the disruption caused by the devices was genuine, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only sporadic reports of pilots arguing for aircraft systems to be disrupted by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the devices when landing in low visibility.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them a sensible adjustment for travelers who would now be well-equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
