Royal Commission hearing: Two YMCA staff charged with sex offences over Jonathan Lord allegations
Two YMCA staff from NSW were charged with child sex offences before allegations were made against Caringbah nanny Jonathan Lord in 2011, the Royal Commission into Child Sexual Abuse has heard.
But in its opening statement to the commission, the YMCA said it had "never dealt with an incident of child sexual abuse within the organisation."
Chief executive Phillip Hare was questioned about one case in which a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another in which a PE teacher at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of child abuse in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case but did not know about the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA's opening statement to the commission had also been inaccurate in asserting that "there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA has been recognized as being at the forefront of child safety."
On the contrary, evidence before the commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating out of four possible in a Department of Education and Communities quality audit in August of that year.
Mr O'Hare, who started at the YMCA when he was 21, admitted management had failed "downwards from me" in hiring Lord and failed to ensure staff were aware of their obligations to report breaches of child safety guidelines.
Lord was convicted earlier this year of sexual offences against 12 boys during his two years working for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to a minimum of six years in prison.
But Mr O'Hare denied that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented staff from reporting child safety breaches.
Staff testified that they had observed violations, including Lord being alone with children, privately babysitting them, letting them sit on his lap, telling one he loved it, and letting children play with his cell phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that children's services director Jacqui Barnat, who was Lord's supervisor at YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and most of the time very aloof."
The managing director said he would not accept statements from staff that they had not dared report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, her friendship with Lord affected her judgment, which is why they did not report him.
Mr O'Hare said he had communicated his view to the YMCA NSW board that the lesson the organisation had to learn from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was "not about reporting" by staff, and the board had agreed.
Mr O'Hare said the decision to press staff to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations emerged was made by Liam Whitley, chief executive of the YMCA's children's services.
He said this was to prevent contamination of the evidence, but it was "overzealous" and poorly implemented.
YMCA NSW was not a child-safe organisation when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Griffith University sexual abuse expert Professor Stephen Smallbone told the commission.
