Scientists have been able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog's tail wagging and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say other dogs can sense these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: 'In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres react differently to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions.'
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, as in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different emotional roles.
To learn more about how dogs react to their counterparts "lateral wagging of tails, the researchers monitored the animals while watching films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analysed their behaviour.
We will probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction or the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: 'We showed the dogs films with dogs - either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.'
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved its tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the inclination of the tail was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not communicate intentionally with each other through these movements.
On the contrary, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience which movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: 'When you have different encounters with other dogs and the tail wagging in one direction is more associated with friendly behaviour and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behaviour, then you react on the basis of those experiences.'
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pet's emotions.
John Bradshaw, a dog behaviour expert and visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, it said: 'Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail is wagging on the left rather than on the right, rather than becoming restless - the opposite of what was found in the Italian study.'
According to him, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he said.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
However, since their behaviour can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
