Desperate cry from an Obama voter
I voted for President Obama twice in the hope that change was possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts thwarted by Republican obstructionism
Blocking policy does not excuse Obamacare website problems, drone strikes
Obama's 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what might have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a terribly sad book at the moment.
It's a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope during the dismal second year of my medical studies.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and tells the story of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential election memoir.
When I finish my patient notes in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take your breath away.
The election turned into a landslide victory, and news anchors paused to reflect on the historic significance of the moment.
My classmates were crying with joy and my parents were collecting all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his approval rating was 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a rude awakening, like being torn from a dream.
It is hard to remember these optimistic times - they seem to be a vague reminder, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, things have indeed changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and diverse things Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I agree that partisan gridlock has overturned too many aspirations to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and closing Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But having defended the Obama administration to colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have reached the end of my explanation.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows foreign heads of state to be wiretapped or innocent children to be killed by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans "private lives, and why whistleblowers who expose government wrongdoing are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the findings of a report that said the White House's efforts to silence the media were the "most aggressive... since the Nixon administration."
And most recently, it can't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if it's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work could be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, being an MP is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and fortuitous events such as the Newtown massacre shape public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely chosen by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and half-baked alternative; he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressures of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had been hearing about for so long.
But with Obama's approval rating dropping below 45% this week, the book's return to 2008 has become all the harder.
It awakens in me a yearning for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week, I read a section in the book describing how Obama suffered a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with election officials after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more with you.
The opinions expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
