Egypt swears in first freely elected president
Mohammed Morsi takes the oath of office, but his day of triumph is unlikely to spell the end of Egypt's political disputes.
Islamist Mohammed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was sworn in as the country's first freely elected president, succeeding Hosni Mubarak, who had been ousted 16 months earlier.
With his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the Arab world's first freely elected Islamist president and Egypt's fifth head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took the oath before the 18 black-robed judges of the court, which sits on the Nile and is modelled on an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We seek a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at the ceremony, which was broadcast live on state television.
"Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations for a new life - absolute freedom, true democracy, and stability," said Morsi, 60, a U.S.-trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been sharply targeted by the government since it was founded 84 years ago as a banned organization.
Hundreds of soldiers and police officers were guarding the building when Morsi arrived in a small convoy of cars shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered outside the court to cheer the new president, and, unlike Mubarak-era presidential pomp, traffic was halted only briefly so that the convoy could cross the usually busy road that connects the city center with the southern suburbs.
Mocked as the Brotherhood's uncharismatic "spare wheel," his personal prestige has grown since his victory and a Friday speech in which he presented himself not only as a candidate for Islamists, but for all who sought to achieve the aspirations of the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional, and modern state," Morsi, dressed in a blue suit and red tie, told the judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he took the oath of office.
Morsi later drove to Cairo University, where he was to deliver his inaugural address.
