The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
Cameroon has only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
By contrast, in the United States, the ratio is one doctor for every 413 people.
But even if they had a doctor, most Cameroonians would not be able to afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health spending is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
Dr Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive with their medical equipment strapped to their roofs over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Everything does not always go smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like heroes: a banquet, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebration, and Bwelle - with his broad smile and boundless energy - is happy to be part of the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will begin examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," Bwelle said.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village - and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates - a document required for school, but which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, a town hall or an apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is supplied by the group's generator, so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It is an exhausting schedule, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team will head back to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group - a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students - has carried out 700 free surgeries in the past year and knows that its work makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free hernia surgery he received now allows him to work again.
"This is changing the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, Bwelle says, he finances 60% of his charitable work, with the rest coming from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Bwelle's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain hands-on experience they would never get at home.
"We can be in surgeries where we help to swab blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
Once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
"He's unquestionably a hero," O'Malley said.
He dedicates his life to this organisation and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, fulfilling a promise he made to his father, is a source of great joy to him.
"I'm so happy to be doing this job," Bwelle said.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
