Tourism: Descent to the Romans
A sewer from Roman times has been preserved at a length of around 120 metres below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you cannot miss the cathedral.
The two towers rise around 157 metres into the sky, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree steeples, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne underworld.
Meeting point for his guided tours is the service centre of Cologne Tourism directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city walls.
Most of the users of the car park therefore today also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site in the parking deck D2, which is separated by metal bars.
You can see ruins about five meters high made of palm-sized stones.
"They are remnants of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants take a look into a dark shaft 15 meters deep on the upper level of the park.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
Next stop of the tour is the praetorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
We are witnessing the official residence of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetorian guard of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for" Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium, "which in plain English means" city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinensi, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the cult of the emperor. ""
And the Praetorium is the former palace of governors, the power center of the Roman empire on the Rhine.
From the antechamber of the exhibition there is a tunnel access to the Roman sewer, which has been preserved here along a length of around 120 metres.
"You can walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After collecting the key from the cash register, he leads the group to a walkable shaft 16 metres deep.
"We are now in the mikvah, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground in order to get the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual ablutions.
To this day, the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, shows different water levels due to changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikvah will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction is expected to begin shortly.
However, it will take several years before it is completed.
Leg almost chopped off: New edition of rocker trial
A bloody attack in the rocker milieu is rolled out again after more than four years.
A trial for attempted manslaughter, grievous bodily harm and property damage against two 30-year-olds has begun at the Regional Court of Frankfurt (Oder).
It is accompanied by strict security measures.
The defendants remained silent at the start.
They are said to have been active in the rocker scene and to have belonged to the Bandidos at that time.
The public prosecutor's office accuses them, together with unknown accomplices, of stabbing and hitting three men in a car in Finowfurt in June 2009.
All the victims were seriously injured, and one man nearly lost his leg.
The victims are said to have belonged to rival group Hells Angels.
One is said to have been a senior member from Berlin.
It appeared to have been preceded by a multi-car chase.
According to the indictment, it was about turf battles and a demonstration of power.
The two defendants were acquitted in an initial trial in early 2012.
A court spokesman said at the time that it could not be proved that the men were actually involved in the bloody feud.
The perpetrators were wearing masks and had not been identified.
The Federal Court of Justice annulled the verdict after an appeal by the public prosecutor's office and referred it back to the regional court for retrial.
One of the defendants is currently in open prison for another offence.
At the beginning, the focus was on the reconstruction of the events on the night of the crime.
The commissioner investigating at the time was called as a witness.
At the center were cell phone conversations of the defendants and other people that the police had bugged.
Difficult is that rockers almost always abide by an iron law in court - and don't testify.
This also applies to the victims.
In the first trial, only one of the victims had unpacked.
Prosecutor Stefan Golfier from the public prosecutor's office in Frankfurt (Oder) said when asked that new traces had emerged since the last trial.
Eleven more days of hearings are scheduled for the trial.
The throwaway society doesn't think
The night was long, the music loud and the mood good, but at some point we go home.
The only difference is that hunger is noticeable in the bellies of the people in the passenger and back seats.
Of course, one or two cocktails or sparkling wines may be to blame!
What could be more obvious than chilling out and heading to the next drive-in to treat yourself to a snack?
I admit I like to be there when it comes to getting fast food late at night or early in the morning.
A few fries, a Coke, a burger - and then go home and go to bed!
But on the way home, the obvious differences between me and other hungry disco-goers become noticeable.
Because what do you have to miss, that you throw your fast food bags out of the car window with constant regularity?!
Particularly at weekends, discarded paper bags lie on roadsides and in car parks.
"Why?" I wonder.
Are people too stupid to take the bags home to the nearest bin?
It's not just that the paper stuff spoils the landscape.
Bags have already covered transport facilities such as guardrails and thus caused accidents.
But the aforementioned "throwaway society" does not think about such a thing, presumably it does not even know what this word actually means.
If you are on the road more often in the evening, especially with several people in the car, you know what a back seat can look like after a night of partying: clothes, bottles and other garbage pile up there.
A few bags would more or less make no difference - in contrast to the street, where no one wants to trample on the leftovers of other people's food.
I can already see the day coming when cities and municipalities will become too stupid to clear away - and fast food chains will have to pay a deposit for their bags.
Obama's Retreat on Health Care Policy
After fierce criticism, President Obama yesterday backtracked on his oft-repeated, unequivocal promise: "If you like your health insurance, you can keep it."
In recent days, after hundreds of thousands of people received a termination letter from their insurer, Republicans have accused the president of misleading the American public.
Yesterday, Obama put his original promise into perspective.
"The vast majority of people who have working health insurance can keep it," he said during a speech in Boston.
Responding to numerous media reports about the cancellations, Obama urged Americans who have received such notices to look for new insurance on the open market.
This would enable most citizens to obtain better, more comprehensive health insurance for the same price, or more cheaply than predicted.
"They come up with a better deal," he said.
The administration said it was unsurprising that the five percent of the population who bought insurance would have to look for a different rate because their policies did not meet the new standards under the Affordable Care Act.
"I want to say directly to these Americans: They deserve better," Sebelius said at a hearing before the House Energy and Commerce Committee in Washington.
Sebelius, who is in charge of implementing the Affordable Care Act, said the launch of the online platform has been "abysmal" since October.
"I'm as frustrated and angry as everyone else," she said.
I am determined to regain your trust.
That statement by an enraged Sebelius to an aide sitting behind her at yesterday's House hearing was recorded after a dispute with Representative Billy Long, a Republican from Missouri, over whether she should be required to participate in Obamacare.
After more than three hours of hearings, Long repeatedly pressed Sebelius about why the "architect" of the Affordable Care Act didn't voluntarily give up government-sponsored insurance to buy a plan on HealthCare.gov that she now wants to sell to millions of Americans.
