John Kerry says US espionage has' gone too far inappropriately'
John Kerry, in an unexpected admission, hinted at a softening of the US's defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying that espionage had in some cases gone "unreasonably far."
The Foreign Secretary also admitted that he shared responsibility with Barack Obama for switching to "autopilot" when whistleblower Edward Snowden's explosive revelations about the NSA's spying activities became public.
The leaked information has sent the US government into a diplomatic storm of outrage from its allies.
Speaking via video link at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: 'There is no question that the president and I, and others in the administration, learned of some of the things that were going on virtually on autopilot, simply because the ability to do so was there, going back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, September 11.'
He then became the first senior member of the US government to admit that US espionage had crossed a line, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said: 'In some cases it has gone too far.'
The President is determined to provide clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one feels that there is abuse taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent people will not be affected in this process.
Kerry, however, insisted that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance had saved many lives.
He added: 'We are dealing with a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.'
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept it and stop it before it happens?
We have, in fact, prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the murder of people, because we learned of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to allay concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to cooperate with the US in counterterrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to representatives of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terror organizations because of frustration with National Security Agency surveillance.
"It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board in our joint efforts against terrorism," Murphy, who is a first-term Democrat in the Senate and serves as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I am also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger at the NSA programmes.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe have strained relations with some US allies, although the intelligence chief said this week that the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA had monitored the cellphones of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other world leaders.
Director of National Intelligence James Clapper defended spying on allies as necessary, saying it was common practice on both sides.
Amid all the turmoil, Murphy said his office was preparing for a congressional trip later this year and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other MPs taking part are due to be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary was still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations, he also said there would be some "serious words."
He said European governments needed to be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they themselves have been using for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect Europeans' rights, they must also come to terms with the fact that we are not the only ones spying," Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to confront resentment over America's strategy in Syria, Egypt, and Iran, as well as its surveillance activities.
