Australian woman appeals against jail sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney woman who was sentenced to 15 days in jail in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been raped by a taxi driver has appealed against the sentence and has been released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by a provincial court in Phuket on 15 June of making a false statement after she told Thai police that a local taxi driver had raped her in the early hours of Sunday 10 June while two other men were holding her.
Later, however, CCTV footage showed she had arrived safely at her hotel after being separated from her Australian boyfriend.
Police in Phuket questioned Bamford for two days until she confessed to making up the story.
She was in police custody at the scene until the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than a prison for adult women.
She is the daughter of Peter Tunks, a former Australian rugby league player, who has written to the Department of Foreign Affairs in Canberra asking for help for his daughter.
Tunks told Sydney's Sunday Telegraph the whole family were 'extremely concerned' for his daughter's welfare and wanted her back in Australia.
"We are obviously very concerned, but we hope she is back home as soon as possible," Tunks said.
Bamford has appealed the sentence and is free on 50,000 baht bail.
Australian reports said she is currently on holiday in the resort of Krabi in southern Thailand.
The court heard Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and had been warned that the appeal could also lead to a higher sentence of up to two years in an adult prison.
However, it is also possible that Thailand may seek to improve its tarnished tourist image following the recent murder of travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, leading to an acquittal.
